3.2 Process Safety Information - A!A?68.65:



The Warren Plant keeps a variety of technical documents that are used to help maintain safe operation of the process. These documents address chemical processes and associated hazards, limits for key process parameters, specific inventories, and equipment design basis/configuration information. The Operations Manager has assigned responsibility for maintaining up-to-date process safety information. 

Chemical-specific information, including toxicity information, permissible exposure limits, physical data, reactivity data, corrosivity data, thermal and chemical stability data is provided in MSDSs (material safety data sheets).  MSDSs are made available to all employees and contract personnel.  When applicable, this information is supplemented by documents that specifically address additional concerns. 

Warren also maintains information pertaining to the technology of the process.  The following process related information is available in the HAZOP (Hazard and Operability Study) of the Warren Plant.

(1) A block flow diagram or simplified process flow diagram;

(2) Process chemistry;

(3) Maximum intended inventory;

(4) Safe upper and lower limits for such items as temperatures, pressures, flows or compositions; and,

(5) An evaluation of the consequences of deviations.

The HAZOP also contains information pertaining to the equipment in the process:

(7) Materials of construction;

(8) Piping and instrument diagrams (P&ID's) and Process Flow Drawings (PFDA!A?s);

(9) Electrical classification;

(10) Relief system design and design basis;

(11) Ventilation system design;

(12) Design codes and standards employed;

(13) Material and energy balances for processes built after June 21, 1999; and

(14) Safety systems (e.g. interlocks, detection or suppression systems).

(15) Documentation that equipment complies with recognized and generally accepted good engineering practices.

(16) Equipment design, maintenance, inspection, testing, and safe operation

3.3 Process Hazard Analysis (PHA) - A!A?68.67:



PAPCO has completed an initial process hazard analysis (hazard evaluation) on processes covered by this part.  PAPCO has determined and documented the priority order for conducting process hazard analyses based on a rationale which includes considerations as; extent of the process hazards, number of potentially affected employees, age of the process, and operating history of the process.  The PHA responds to 29 CFR 1910.119(e).  

PAPCO utilized the following methodology, appropriate to determine and evaluate the hazards of the process being analyzed.

Hazard and Operability Study (HAZOP);

The HAZOP addresses:

(1) The hazards of the process;

(2) The identification of any previous incident which had a likely potential for catastrophic consequences.

(3) Engineering and administrative controls applicable to the hazards and their interrelationships such as appropriate application of detection methodologies to provide early warning of releases. 

(4) Consequences of failure of engineering and administrative controls;

(5) Stationary source siting;

(6) Human factors; and

(7) A qualitative evaluation of a range of the possible safety and health effects of failure of controls.

The process hazard analysis was performed by a team with expertise in engineering and process operations.  Don Love, Ph.D, P.E. facilitated the effort.  Dr. Love has over 40 years of experience and knowledge specific to the process being evaluated.  

